      "fontSize": 28,
      "fontFamily": 1,
      "text": "Deep Dive/Improved and Final Design",
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Deep Dive/Improved and Final Design",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "version": 903,
      "versionNonce": 2006232169,
      "index": "b0d",
      "isDeleted": false,
      "id": "EiXQsu12jbgOLeqqbsWh6",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "angle": 0,
      "x": 261.660598121843,
      "y": 1454.832617666782,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "width": 807.41943359375,
      "height": 925,
      "seed": 609548807,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "roundness": null,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1720053704996,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 1,
      "text": "HANDLING TIME WINDOWS\n  - We'll maintain separate Counts for each time window \"Hour\" and \"Day\"\n    as well as separate \"top-k heaps\". We can utilize \"Day\" count for \"Month\".\n\n  - To handle time windows we need to age out views that happened \n    outside that window. One solution could be is to use \n    \"2-pointers/sliding window\".\n  \n      Using 2-Pointers: \n       We can have pointers pulling messages at different offsets from Kafka. \n       - \"Rising edge\", when a new view comes in the system adds this view \n          to the current count for all active time windows (hour, day).\n       \n       - \"Falling edges\" where we decrement the count. \n          For each \"Falling Edge\",\n          * start reading from the Kafka at an offset corresponding to \n            the window (e.g., 1 hour ago, 1 month ago).\n          * We pause consuming when we encounter an entry that is newer \n            than the current time minus the duration of the time window.\n          * This ensures that any views processed by the \"falling edge\" pointers \n            are decremented from the respective counts, as they no longer fall \n            within the current time window.\n\nCHALLENGES: \n - at least a 1 month (+ time since our last snapshot) retention.\n - Increased read load\n - Because, videos may fall out of the top 1,000, we need to make \n   sure our heaps are storing significantly more than 1,000 (say, 2,000) \n   accommodating new entries smoothly and expiration of old entries effectively.\n\n   \nHANDLING LARGE READ REQUEST\n - We can add a cache setup TTL on the cache so results are never \n  more stale than requirement. When a request comes in, we can either \n  serve it from cache or we query all Counters for the given heap of \n  the request and then store the merged values back in the case. \n",
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "HANDLING TIME WINDOWS\n  - We'll maintain separate Counts for each time window \"Hour\" and \"Day\"\n    as well as separate \"top-k heaps\". We can utilize \"Day\" count for \"Month\".\n\n  - To handle time windows we need to age out views that happened \n    outside that window. One solution could be is to use \n    \"2-pointers/sliding window\".\n  \n      Using 2-Pointers: \n       We can have pointers pulling messages at different offsets from Kafka. \n       - \"Rising edge\", when a new view comes in the system adds this view \n          to the current count for all active time windows (hour, day).\n       \n       - \"Falling edges\" where we decrement the count. \n          For each \"Falling Edge\",\n          * start reading from the Kafka at an offset corresponding to \n            the window (e.g., 1 hour ago, 1 month ago).\n          * We pause consuming when we encounter an entry that is newer \n            than the current time minus the duration of the time window.\n          * This ensures that any views processed by the \"falling edge\" pointers \n            are decremented from the respective counts, as they no longer fall \n            within the current time window.\n\nCHALLENGES: \n - at least a 1 month (+ time since our last snapshot) retention.\n - Increased read load\n - Because, videos may fall out of the top 1,000, we need to make \n   sure our heaps are storing significantly more than 1,000 (say, 2,000) \n   accommodating new entries smoothly and expiration of old entries effectively.\n\n   \nHANDLING LARGE READ REQUEST\n - We can add a cache setup TTL on the cache so results are never \n  more stale than requirement. When a request comes in, we can either \n  serve it from cache or we query all Counters for the given heap of \n  the request and then store the merged values back in the case. \n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
