      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "fontSize": 28,
      "fontFamily": 1,
      "text": "Domain-specific rate limiting mechanism using Redis\n -This help us identify whether to fetch web page or not\n - respect the rate limit of 1 domain a second\n - track request count per domain per second",
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Domain-specific rate limiting mechanism using Redis\n -This help us identify whether to fetch web page or not\n - respect the rate limit of 1 domain a second\n - track request count per domain per second",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "version": 440,
      "versionNonce": 1716827161,
      "index": "b24",
      "isDeleted": false,
      "id": "q3UacRwWMM0ffSUcxpX9u",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "angle": 0,
      "x": 2108.5973930460177,
      "y": 4955.3272093750265,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "width": 1121.399658203125,
      "height": 980,
      "seed": 2132906617,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "roundness": null,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1720764586533,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "fontSize": 28,
      "fontFamily": 1,
      "text": "Scale to 10B pages\nIn the AWS ecosystem, a network optimized instance can \nhandle about 400 Gbps. This means that a single instance, \ncan handle about:\n\n(400 Gbps / 8 bits/byte) / 2MB/page = 25,000 pages/second. \n\nThat's a ton. But there will be limitations on the number \nof requests per second dictated by factors like server \nresponse latency, DNS resolution, rate limiting, politeness, retries, etc.\n\nBut let's say we utilize 30% of the available bandwidth. This would \ngive us: \n25,000 pages/second * 30% = 7,500 pages/second i.e. around 10k or 10^4\n\nTo estimate the total number of high powered machines we need, \nwe can divide the total number of pages by the number of pages \nwe can crawl per second. For single machine this gives us,\n\n 10,000,000,000 pages / 7,500 pages/second = 1,333,333 seconds = 15.4 days.\nOR\n10^9/10^4 = 10^6 seconds\n10^6/10^5(seconds in a day) = 10 days on single machine, \n  i.e. if we use 2 machines it will take 5 days\n\n\n\n",
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Scale to 10B pages\nIn the AWS ecosystem, a network optimized instance can \nhandle about 400 Gbps. This means that a single instance, \ncan handle about:\n\n(400 Gbps / 8 bits/byte) / 2MB/page = 25,000 pages/second. \n\nThat's a ton. But there will be limitations on the number \nof requests per second dictated by factors like server \nresponse latency, DNS resolution, rate limiting, politeness, retries, etc.\n\nBut let's say we utilize 30% of the available bandwidth. This would \ngive us: \n25,000 pages/second * 30% = 7,500 pages/second i.e. around 10k or 10^4\n\nTo estimate the total number of high powered machines we need, \nwe can divide the total number of pages by the number of pages \nwe can crawl per second. For single machine this gives us,\n\n 10,000,000,000 pages / 7,500 pages/second = 1,333,333 seconds = 15.4 days.\nOR\n10^9/10^4 = 10^6 seconds\n10^6/10^5(seconds in a day) = 10 days on single machine, \n  i.e. if we use 2 machines it will take 5 days\n\n\n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
