    {
      "type": "text",
      "version": 1520,
      "versionNonce": 271660798,
      "index": "bBy",
      "isDeleted": false,
      "id": "3NmBEHwDcw2dgsW1xP5dB",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "angle": 0,
      "x": 3688.1538436798955,
      "y": 27596.286901546737,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "width": 946.187266160189,
      "height": 636.8679306100929,
      "seed": 1665071394,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "roundness": null,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1729142637683,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "fontSize": 28.305241360448573,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "text": "Redis (with Lua Scripting)\n\nWhy:\n - Offers extremely fast reads and writes \n   for rule evaluation.\n - Cache frequently accessed data \n    (e.g., popular stocks with many rules).\n - Lua scripting: Can be used to pre-evaluate stock \n   prices in the cache and return alerts in milliseconds.\nData Model:\n - Store stock-specific rules as sorted sets or hashes.\n - Use Lua scripts to evaluate thresholds and rules directly \n    in-memory without extra reads.\nCaveats:\n - Memory constraints: May require significant memory for \n   storing millions of rules, though Redis can persist data to disk.\n - Not suitable as a primary database for massive datasets, \n    but works well as a caching layer for rule evaluation.",
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Redis (with Lua Scripting)\n\nWhy:\n - Offers extremely fast reads and writes \n   for rule evaluation.\n - Cache frequently accessed data \n    (e.g., popular stocks with many rules).\n - Lua scripting: Can be used to pre-evaluate stock \n   prices in the cache and return alerts in milliseconds.\nData Model:\n - Store stock-specific rules as sorted sets or hashes.\n - Use Lua scripts to evaluate thresholds and rules directly \n    in-memory without extra reads.\nCaveats:\n - Memory constraints: May require significant memory for \n   storing millions of rules, though Redis can persist data to disk.\n - Not suitable as a primary database for massive datasets, \n    but works well as a caching layer for rule evaluation.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "version": 227,
      "versionNonce": 761142690,
      "index": "bBz",
      "isDeleted": false,
      "id": "vo3Vs2hiNrTtno9Q_c7P0",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "angle": 0,
      "x": 4981.107708820606,
      "y": 29262.11111745947,
      "strokeColor": "#f08c00",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "width": 1269.4675674438477,
      "height": 990,
      "seed": 2132089762,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "roundness": null,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1729138478942,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "text": "** Another Recommended Approach for DB **\n\nPrimary Storage: Cassandra/ScyllaDB\n * Why: Cassandra’s distributed nature, horizontal scalability, \n   and low-latency reads make it an excellent choice for storing \n   and querying millions of stock rules.\n * How It Works:\n    - Partition rules by stock symbol.\n    - Query for rules related to a specific stock symbol and rule \n      type in constant time (using Cassandra’s partition key).\n    - Efficiently scale as the number of rules grows, without \n      worrying about pagination or scroll mechanisms.\n\nSecondary Storage: Redis for Caching Hot Data\n * Why: Redis can act as a caching layer for frequently accessed \n    stocks and rules. For example, if a certain stock price changes \n    frequently or has a high number of subscribers, caching those \n    rules in Redis would allow faster rule evaluation.\n * How It Works:\n    - Cache stock rules in Redis for quick lookups during evaluation.\n    - Use Redis for frequently accessed rules, while Cassandra serves \n      as the primary store for all rules.",
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "** Another Recommended Approach for DB **\n\nPrimary Storage: Cassandra/ScyllaDB\n * Why: Cassandra’s distributed nature, horizontal scalability, \n   and low-latency reads make it an excellent choice for storing \n   and querying millions of stock rules.\n * How It Works:\n    - Partition rules by stock symbol.\n    - Query for rules related to a specific stock symbol and rule \n      type in constant time (using Cassandra’s partition key).\n    - Efficiently scale as the number of rules grows, without \n      worrying about pagination or scroll mechanisms.\n\nSecondary Storage: Redis for Caching Hot Data\n * Why: Redis can act as a caching layer for frequently accessed \n    stocks and rules. For example, if a certain stock price changes \n    frequently or has a high number of subscribers, caching those \n    rules in Redis would allow faster rule evaluation.\n * How It Works:\n    - Cache stock rules in Redis for quick lookups during evaluation.\n    - Use Redis for frequently accessed rules, while Cassandra serves \n      as the primary store for all rules.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
