      "updated": 1729916030602,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "fontSize": 45.250883384124606,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "text": "Uber Driver Location (2 requirements)",
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Uber Driver Location (2 requirements)",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "version": 314,
      "versionNonce": 1670498573,
      "index": "bD7",
      "isDeleted": false,
      "id": "9MPLqfv84nJ1rCzd4VOtB",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "angle": 0,
      "x": 77.04564317294717,
      "y": 35664.46964304723,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "width": 3256.5471689068595,
      "height": 690.518536915584,
      "seed": 1457137357,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "roundness": null,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1729988851579,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "fontSize": 46.034569127705595,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "text": "In ride hailing service, Drivers upload their locations every second. Design a system that takes data and allows us to serve a heat map of their\nlocations\n\nRequirement 1: \nWe want to build a tool for our operations folks. They need to monitor the health of their city in real time. We need to serve the last 20\nminutes of data for this tool. We want to split up the data into one minute buckets for each of those 20 minutes (thus yielding 20 different\nsets of data we can visualize).\n\nRequirement 2: \nWe want to expose this data for consumption by cities and research institutions. Since it will be used for research purposes, we do not need\ndata in real time. The data need only be available after 24 hours. Furthermore, we will summarize the data over the hour (rather than the\nminute above) and this data can only be requested in full hour increments (12:00-16:00 but not 12:05-16:05)",
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "In ride hailing service, Drivers upload their locations every second. Design a system that takes data and allows us to serve a heat map of their locations\n\nRequirement 1: \nWe want to build a tool for our operations folks. They need to monitor the health of their city in real time. We need to serve the last 20 minutes of data for this tool. We want to split up the data into one minute buckets for each of those 20 minutes (thus yielding 20 different sets of data we can visualize).\n\nRequirement 2: \nWe want to expose this data for consumption by cities and research institutions. Since it will be used for research purposes, we do not need data in real time. The data need only be available after 24 hours. Furthermore, we will summarize the data over the hour (rather than the minute above) and this data can only be requested in full hour increments (12:00-16:00 but not 12:05-16:05)",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "version": 273,
      "versionNonce": 1989586061,
      "index": "bD8",
      "isDeleted": false,
      "id": "Ka8VSnD89N0cQD8V29cfg",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "angle": 0,
      "x": 84.02787655996599,
      "y": 36507.92966270206,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "width": 2351.553308627515,
      "height": 3595.705040556398,
      "seed": 1072638157,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "roundness": null,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1729988864994,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "fontSize": 36.87902605698872,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "text": "\nFunctional Req:\n - Ingest driver location data every second.\n - Store the last 20 minutes of location data.\n - Aggregate data into 1-minute buckets.\n - Serve the data as a heat map for operations to visualize real-time city health.\n\nNon-Functional Req:\n - Low Latency: The system must provide near-real-time updates for location data.\n - Scalability: Handle high data ingestion rates due to thousands of drivers reporting locations every second.\n - Availability: The system should be highly available to ensure the tool is accessible at all times.\n - Fault Tolerance: Ensure data persistence in the case of failures.\n\nBack-of-the-Envelope:\n- Data Ingestion Rate: Assume 10,000 drivers per city, with each driver sending 1 update per second\n      Data rate = 10,000 updates/sec.\n\n - Storage for 1 minute of data:\n       Each location update contains driver_id, timestamp, lat, lon (40 bytes).\n       Storage per minute = 10,000 * 40 bytes = 400 KB.\n       Storage for 20 minutes = 20 * 400 KB = 8 MB per city.\n\n - Queries per Second: Assume 100 operations staff accessing the tool.\n        If each user generates 1 query every 5 seconds, then 20 QPS.\n\nAPI Endpoints:\n\n - POST /location: Accepts real-time location updates from drivers.\n        Request: { \"driver_id\": \"string\", \"timestamp\": \"ISO 8601\", \"lat\": float, \"lon\": float }\n\n - GET /heatmap?city_id={city_id}&start={timestamp}&end={timestamp}: Retrieves heat map data for a given time range.\n        Response: { \"timestamp\": \"ISO 8601\", \"buckets\": [{ \"minute\": int, \"data\": [{ \"lat\": float, \"lon\": float, \"count\": int }] }] }\n\n\nDatabase Tables:\n    - RealTime_Locations (city_id, driver_id, timestamp, lat, lon)\n\n    - Minute_Buckets:\n        city_id, \n        minute_timestamp (rounded to the minute)\n        location_count\n        lat_lon_grid (serialized data representing location densities)\n\n\nFinal Design Diagram for Requirement 1:\n\nComponents:\n - API Gateway: \n     Handles requests and routes them to relevant services.\n - Location Ingestor Service: \n     Accepts location data, validates it, and sends it to a stream.\n - Stream Processor (e.g., Apache Kafka, Flink): \n     Aggregates location data into minute buckets and writes to a time-series DB.\n - Time-Series Database (e.g., InfluxDB): \n      Stores the aggregated data for 20 minutes, allowing for efficient retrieval.\n - Heat Map Service: \n      Fetches the data from the time-series database and formats it for visualization.\n - Cache (e.g., Redis): \n     Caches recent minute-level data for quick access by the Heat Map Service.\n\nDeep Dive into Major Components:\n\n - Location Ingestor Service:\n    *Responsible for processing high-frequency location updates from drivers.\n    *Writes the data into a stream for further processing.\n    *Performs basic validation (e.g., checking timestamp format).\n \n- Stream Processor:\n    *Aggregates data into 1-minute buckets based on time and geospatial regions.\n    *Writes aggregated data to a time-series database.\n\n - Time-Series Database:\n    *Optimized for time-based queries, allowing efficient retrieval of data for the last 20 minutes.\n    *Retains only the last 20 minutes of data, evicting older data.\n\n - Heat Map Service:\n    *Queries the time-series database for recent data.\n    *Processes data into a heat map format, using geospatial libraries to map densities.",
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "\nFunctional Req:\n - Ingest driver location data every second.\n - Store the last 20 minutes of location data.\n - Aggregate data into 1-minute buckets.\n - Serve the data as a heat map for operations to visualize real-time city health.\n\nNon-Functional Req:\n - Low Latency: The system must provide near-real-time updates for location data.\n - Scalability: Handle high data ingestion rates due to thousands of drivers reporting locations every second.\n - Availability: The system should be highly available to ensure the tool is accessible at all times.\n - Fault Tolerance: Ensure data persistence in the case of failures.\n\nBack-of-the-Envelope:\n- Data Ingestion Rate: Assume 10,000 drivers per city, with each driver sending 1 update per second\n      Data rate = 10,000 updates/sec.\n\n - Storage for 1 minute of data:\n       Each location update contains driver_id, timestamp, lat, lon (40 bytes).\n       Storage per minute = 10,000 * 40 bytes = 400 KB.\n       Storage for 20 minutes = 20 * 400 KB = 8 MB per city.\n\n - Queries per Second: Assume 100 operations staff accessing the tool.\n        If each user generates 1 query every 5 seconds, then 20 QPS.\n\nAPI Endpoints:\n\n - POST /location: Accepts real-time location updates from drivers.\n        Request: { \"driver_id\": \"string\", \"timestamp\": \"ISO 8601\", \"lat\": float, \"lon\": float }\n\n - GET /heatmap?city_id={city_id}&start={timestamp}&end={timestamp}: Retrieves heat map data for a given time range.\n        Response: { \"timestamp\": \"ISO 8601\", \"buckets\": [{ \"minute\": int, \"data\": [{ \"lat\": float, \"lon\": float, \"count\": int }] }] }\n\n\nDatabase Tables:\n    - RealTime_Locations (city_id, driver_id, timestamp, lat, lon)\n\n    - Minute_Buckets:\n        city_id, \n        minute_timestamp (rounded to the minute)\n        location_count\n        lat_lon_grid (serialized data representing location densities)\n\n\nFinal Design Diagram for Requirement 1:\n\nComponents:\n - API Gateway: \n     Handles requests and routes them to relevant services.\n - Location Ingestor Service: \n     Accepts location data, validates it, and sends it to a stream.\n - Stream Processor (e.g., Apache Kafka, Flink): \n     Aggregates location data into minute buckets and writes to a time-series DB.\n - Time-Series Database (e.g., InfluxDB): \n      Stores the aggregated data for 20 minutes, allowing for efficient retrieval.\n - Heat Map Service: \n      Fetches the data from the time-series database and formats it for visualization.\n - Cache (e.g., Redis): \n     Caches recent minute-level data for quick access by the Heat Map Service.\n\nDeep Dive into Major Components:\n\n - Location Ingestor Service:\n    *Responsible for processing high-frequency location updates from drivers.\n    *Writes the data into a stream for further processing.\n    *Performs basic validation (e.g., checking timestamp format).\n \n- Stream Processor:\n    *Aggregates data into 1-minute buckets based on time and geospatial regions.\n    *Writes aggregated data to a time-series database.\n\n - Time-Series Database:\n    *Optimized for time-based queries, allowing efficient retrieval of data for the last 20 minutes.\n    *Retains only the last 20 minutes of data, evicting older data.\n\n - Heat Map Service:\n    *Queries the time-series database for recent data.\n    *Processes data into a heat map format, using geospatial libraries to map densities.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
