    {
      "type": "text",
      "version": 261,
      "versionNonce": 908891085,
      "index": "bDD",
      "isDeleted": false,
      "id": "_k-z4p6ikq50TnMDICykW",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "angle": 0,
      "x": 169.846219746388,
      "y": 40304.75105439805,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "width": 2375.074529591326,
      "height": 2812.584321327441,
      "seed": 1435394051,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "roundness": null,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1729988872227,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "fontSize": 39.47486766775364,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "text": "1. Functional Requirements:\n - Summarize driver location data over 1-hour intervals.\n - Store data for 24 hours.\n - Provide data for download in full-hour increments (e.g., 12:00-13:00).\n\n2. Non-Functional Requirements:\n - Data Consistency: Ensure that the summarized data is accurate.\n - Durability: Summarized data should be stored securely for 24 hours.\n - Accessibility: Provide a simple interface for external entities to access and download data.\n\n3. Back-of-the-Envelope Estimation:\n - Data Summarization Rate: Assume 10,000 drivers sending location data every second.\n     *36,000,000 updates per hour.\n     *Summarization reduces the data to lat-lon buckets with counts.\n \n - Storage for 1 hour of summarized data:\n     *Aggregated data per hour ≈ 100 KB.\n     *For 24 hours = 2.4 MB per city.\n\n\n4. API Endpoints:\n     - Retrieves summarized data for a given time range.\n        GET /summary?city_id={city_id}&start={timestamp}&end={timestamp}: \n        Response: { \"hour\": \"ISO 8601\", \"data\": [{ \"lat\": float, \"lon\": float, \"count\": int }] }\n\n\n5. Extended Database Tables:\n\n    Hourly_Summary:\n        city_id\n        hour_timestamp (rounded to the hour)\n        location_count\n        lat_lon_grid (serialized data representing location densities)\n\n\n6. Final Design Diagram for Requirement 2:\n\n   - Components (New/Updated):\n        Batch Processor: Processes data from the stream every hour to create summarized data.\n        Object Storage (e.g., S3): Stores hourly summarized data files for 24 hours.\n        Research Data Service: Provides an interface for external entities to access and download the summarized data.\n\n7. Deep Dive into Major Components (Extension):\n    - Batch Processor:\n        *Runs every hour to process and summarize the last hour's location data.\n        *Writes summarized data into object storage for further retrieval.\n    \n    - Object Storage (S3):\n        *Stores hourly data, providing durable storage and allowing for easy retrieval of data by external clients.\n\n    - Research Data Service:\n        *Handles access control and data retrieval requests.\n        *Ensures that data is delivered in the correct format and respects full-hour time boundaries.\n\n\nThis design ensures a scalable and efficient solution for both real-time operational monitoring and delayed research data\naccess, optimizing for different latency and storage requirements in each case.",
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "1. Functional Requirements:\n - Summarize driver location data over 1-hour intervals.\n - Store data for 24 hours.\n - Provide data for download in full-hour increments (e.g., 12:00-13:00).\n\n2. Non-Functional Requirements:\n - Data Consistency: Ensure that the summarized data is accurate.\n - Durability: Summarized data should be stored securely for 24 hours.\n - Accessibility: Provide a simple interface for external entities to access and download data.\n\n3. Back-of-the-Envelope Estimation:\n - Data Summarization Rate: Assume 10,000 drivers sending location data every second.\n     *36,000,000 updates per hour.\n     *Summarization reduces the data to lat-lon buckets with counts.\n \n - Storage for 1 hour of summarized data:\n     *Aggregated data per hour ≈ 100 KB.\n     *For 24 hours = 2.4 MB per city.\n\n\n4. API Endpoints:\n     - Retrieves summarized data for a given time range.\n        GET /summary?city_id={city_id}&start={timestamp}&end={timestamp}: \n        Response: { \"hour\": \"ISO 8601\", \"data\": [{ \"lat\": float, \"lon\": float, \"count\": int }] }\n\n\n5. Extended Database Tables:\n\n    Hourly_Summary:\n        city_id\n        hour_timestamp (rounded to the hour)\n        location_count\n        lat_lon_grid (serialized data representing location densities)\n\n\n6. Final Design Diagram for Requirement 2:\n\n   - Components (New/Updated):\n        Batch Processor: Processes data from the stream every hour to create summarized data.\n        Object Storage (e.g., S3): Stores hourly summarized data files for 24 hours.\n        Research Data Service: Provides an interface for external entities to access and download the summarized data.\n\n7. Deep Dive into Major Components (Extension):\n    - Batch Processor:\n        *Runs every hour to process and summarize the last hour's location data.\n        *Writes summarized data into object storage for further retrieval.\n    \n    - Object Storage (S3):\n        *Stores hourly data, providing durable storage and allowing for easy retrieval of data by external clients.\n\n    - Research Data Service:\n        *Handles access control and data retrieval requests.\n        *Ensures that data is delivered in the correct format and respects full-hour time boundaries.\n\n\nThis design ensures a scalable and efficient solution for both real-time operational monitoring and delayed research data access, optimizing for different latency and storage requirements in each case.",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
