      "fontSize": 68.06171603180479,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "text": "Distributed Job/Task Scheduler\n",
      "textAlign": "center",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Distributed Job/Task Scheduler\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "version": 408,
      "versionNonce": 1243856424,
      "index": "bET",
      "isDeleted": false,
      "id": "jkoPtLbf6pC6_UrVjbvi-",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "angle": 0,
      "x": -667.0837156259593,
      "y": 44495.45574066099,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "width": 1842.6953125,
      "height": 5265,
      "seed": 597332877,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "roundness": null,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1756065150438,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "text": "1. Functional Requirements\n - Job Registration: \n    Users can create, update, and delete jobs. Jobs may have specific schedules, \n    recurrence intervals, and dependencies on other jobs.\n - Job Execution: \n    Execute jobs at their specified time or upon meeting conditions \n    (e.g., cron jobs, interval-based jobs, or event-driven tasks).\n - Job Monitoring: \n    Track the status of each job (pending, running, completed, failed, or retried). \n    Allow users to query the status and history of jobs.\n - Job Retry: \n    Automatically retry failed jobs based on pre-configured retry policies.\n - Job Priority: \n    Handle jobs with varying priorities to ensure that critical jobs are processed first.\n - Task Dependencies: \n    Support dependencies between jobs, ensuring jobs that rely on other jobs only \n    execute once their dependencies are complete.\n - Job Cancellation: Allow users to cancel or pause running jobs.\n - Concurrency Control: \n    Handle concurrent job executions while avoiding resource conflicts.\n - Alerting and Notifications: Notify users of job failures, successes, or retry attempts \n    through email or webhooks.\n - Scalability: Ability to scale horizontally to handle a large number of jobs and distribute \n    them across multiple nodes.\n\n\n2. Non-Functional Requirements\n - Scalability: \n    The system should support horizontal scaling to handle an increasing \n    number of jobs and execute them efficiently.\n - High Availability: \n    Ensure the scheduler is highly available and can tolerate node failures \n    without job loss.\n - Fault Tolerance: \n    The system should gracefully recover from failures and continue processing jobs.\n - Low Latency: \n    Minimize the delay between job scheduling and execution, especially for time-sensitive jobs.\n - Data Consistency: \n    Ensure that job state (e.g., pending, running, completed) is consistent across all nodes.\n - Throughput: \n    Support a high number of job executions per second to meet user demand.\n - Security: \n    Ensure secure access to APIs, data encryption, and secure storage of user credentials and job data.\n - Monitoring and Logging: \n    Provide detailed logging and metrics for monitoring job executions and system performance.\n - Multi-tenancy: Support multiple users or teams, ensuring data isolation between different tenants.\n\n\n3. Back-of-the-Envelope Estimation\n - Number of Jobs: \n    Assume 1 million jobs scheduled daily, with peaks of 10,000 jobs per second.\n - Job Storage: \n    Each job record (metadata, status) is around 1 KB. Storing 1 million job records \n    requires around 1 GB of storage per day.\n - Job History Retention: \n    Retain job history for 30 days, leading to a data storage of ~30 GB.\n - API Requests: \n    Assuming 10,000 API requests per second for job management (create, update, delete, status).\n - Number of Nodes: \n    With an average job execution time of 2 seconds, around 500 worker nodes could handle the load, \n    considering 20 jobs per node per second.\n\n\n4. API Endpoints\n - Job Management\n\n    POST /jobs: Create a new job.\n    PUT /jobs/{job_id}: Update job details.\n    DELETE /jobs/{job_id}: Delete a job.\n    GET /jobs/{job_id}: Get details of a specific job.\n    GET /jobs: List all jobs with filtering options (status, priority, time range).\n \n- Job Execution and Status\n\n    POST /jobs/{job_id}/run: Trigger a job immediately.\n    GET /jobs/{job_id}/status: Get the current status of a job.\n    GET /jobs/{job_id}/logs: Retrieve execution logs of a job.\n    POST /jobs/{job_id}/cancel: Cancel a running job.\n\n - Job Monitoring\n\n    GET /jobs/history: Get historical data for jobs within a time range.\n    POST /jobs/{job_id}/retry: Manually retry a failed job.\n    \n - Alerts and Notifications\n\n    POST /alerts: Configure alerts for job completion/failure.\n\n\n\n5. Database Tables (Field Names Only)\n - Jobs\n    job_id (UUID)\n    name\n    schedule (cron expression or time interval)\n    priority (integer)\n    retry_policy (max_attempts, delay between retries)\n    status (pending, running, completed, failed)\n    created_at, updated_at\n    \n - Job Dependencies\n    job_id (UUID)\n    depends_on (UUID of the job this job depends on)\n    \n - Job Executions\n    execution_id (UUID)\n    job_id (UUID)\n    status (running, completed, failed)\n    start_time, end_time\n    logs (text or URL to logs)\n    \n - Job Alerts\n    alert_id (UUID)\n    job_id (UUID)\n    type (success, failure)\n    notification_method (email, webhook)\n    contact_details (email address or webhook URL)",
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "1. Functional Requirements\n - Job Registration: \n    Users can create, update, and delete jobs. Jobs may have specific schedules, \n    recurrence intervals, and dependencies on other jobs.\n - Job Execution: \n    Execute jobs at their specified time or upon meeting conditions \n    (e.g., cron jobs, interval-based jobs, or event-driven tasks).\n - Job Monitoring: \n    Track the status of each job (pending, running, completed, failed, or retried). \n    Allow users to query the status and history of jobs.\n - Job Retry: \n    Automatically retry failed jobs based on pre-configured retry policies.\n - Job Priority: \n    Handle jobs with varying priorities to ensure that critical jobs are processed first.\n - Task Dependencies: \n    Support dependencies between jobs, ensuring jobs that rely on other jobs only \n    execute once their dependencies are complete.\n - Job Cancellation: Allow users to cancel or pause running jobs.\n - Concurrency Control: \n    Handle concurrent job executions while avoiding resource conflicts.\n - Alerting and Notifications: Notify users of job failures, successes, or retry attempts \n    through email or webhooks.\n - Scalability: Ability to scale horizontally to handle a large number of jobs and distribute \n    them across multiple nodes.\n\n\n2. Non-Functional Requirements\n - Scalability: \n    The system should support horizontal scaling to handle an increasing \n    number of jobs and execute them efficiently.\n - High Availability: \n    Ensure the scheduler is highly available and can tolerate node failures \n    without job loss.\n - Fault Tolerance: \n    The system should gracefully recover from failures and continue processing jobs.\n - Low Latency: \n    Minimize the delay between job scheduling and execution, especially for time-sensitive jobs.\n - Data Consistency: \n    Ensure that job state (e.g., pending, running, completed) is consistent across all nodes.\n - Throughput: \n    Support a high number of job executions per second to meet user demand.\n - Security: \n    Ensure secure access to APIs, data encryption, and secure storage of user credentials and job data.\n - Monitoring and Logging: \n    Provide detailed logging and metrics for monitoring job executions and system performance.\n - Multi-tenancy: Support multiple users or teams, ensuring data isolation between different tenants.\n\n\n3. Back-of-the-Envelope Estimation\n - Number of Jobs: \n    Assume 1 million jobs scheduled daily, with peaks of 10,000 jobs per second.\n - Job Storage: \n    Each job record (metadata, status) is around 1 KB. Storing 1 million job records \n    requires around 1 GB of storage per day.\n - Job History Retention: \n    Retain job history for 30 days, leading to a data storage of ~30 GB.\n - API Requests: \n    Assuming 10,000 API requests per second for job management (create, update, delete, status).\n - Number of Nodes: \n    With an average job execution time of 2 seconds, around 500 worker nodes could handle the load, \n    considering 20 jobs per node per second.\n\n\n4. API Endpoints\n - Job Management\n\n    POST /jobs: Create a new job.\n    PUT /jobs/{job_id}: Update job details.\n    DELETE /jobs/{job_id}: Delete a job.\n    GET /jobs/{job_id}: Get details of a specific job.\n    GET /jobs: List all jobs with filtering options (status, priority, time range).\n \n- Job Execution and Status\n\n    POST /jobs/{job_id}/run: Trigger a job immediately.\n    GET /jobs/{job_id}/status: Get the current status of a job.\n    GET /jobs/{job_id}/logs: Retrieve execution logs of a job.\n    POST /jobs/{job_id}/cancel: Cancel a running job.\n\n - Job Monitoring\n\n    GET /jobs/history: Get historical data for jobs within a time range.\n    POST /jobs/{job_id}/retry: Manually retry a failed job.\n    \n - Alerts and Notifications\n\n    POST /alerts: Configure alerts for job completion/failure.\n\n\n\n5. Database Tables (Field Names Only)\n - Jobs\n    job_id (UUID)\n    name\n    schedule (cron expression or time interval)\n    priority (integer)\n    retry_policy (max_attempts, delay between retries)\n    status (pending, running, completed, failed)\n    created_at, updated_at\n    \n - Job Dependencies\n    job_id (UUID)\n    depends_on (UUID of the job this job depends on)\n    \n - Job Executions\n    execution_id (UUID)\n    job_id (UUID)\n    status (running, completed, failed)\n    start_time, end_time\n    logs (text or URL to logs)\n    \n - Job Alerts\n    alert_id (UUID)\n    job_id (UUID)\n    type (success, failure)\n    notification_method (email, webhook)\n    contact_details (email address or webhook URL)",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "version": 1017,
      "versionNonce": 1733409297,
      "index": "bF0",
      "isDeleted": false,
      "id": "u9F-V25N3_mRQ19ouK3QG",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "angle": 0,
      "x": 5796.2462657643,
      "y": 44421.03892481881,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "width": 2438.8766374867796,
      "height": 4281.803201470554,
      "seed": 734204163,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "roundness": null,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1754711944221,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "fontSize": 37.642225946993875,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "text": " Deep Dive into Major Components\n\n - Job Scheduler (Master Node/Leader)\n\n    * Role: \n        The central component that manages job distribution to worker nodes. \n        It maintains a global job queue and assigns jobs to workers. \n    * Interactions: \n        Reads job data from the database and pushes tasks into the job queue. \n        Continuously monitors worker nodes for job completion or failures.\n    * Considerations: \n        Leader election mechanism is needed for high availability, \n        e.g., using Zookeeper or etcd.\n\n - Job Queue (e.g., Redis, RabbitMQ)\n\n    * Role: \n        Stores jobs in a queue for workers to pick up based on their load. Supports \n        prioritized queues to ensure high-priority jobs are executed first.\n    * Interactions: \n        Worker nodes consume jobs from the queue, and the scheduler pushes new jobs or retries into the queue.\n    * Considerations: \n        Choosing a queue with support for priority handling and message acknowledgment is crucial to prevent job loss.\n\n - Worker Nodes\n\n    * Role: \n        Execute jobs by picking them from the job queue. Each worker updates the status of the job \n        in the database upon completion or failure.\n    * Interactions: \n        Interacts with the job queue to pull tasks and with the database to update job statuses.\n    * Considerations: \n        Workers should be stateless to enable horizontal scaling. Use thread pools within workers\n        for parallel job execution.\n\n - Job Storage (SQL/NoSQL Database) : \n    Use different DB for Job storage (Postgres/DynamoDB/MongoDb) and for log storage (TimeSeries InfluxDB/Elasticsearch). \n    Store archived or old logs to S3.\n\n    * Role: Stores job metadata, schedules, execution logs, and history.\n    * Interactions: Used by the scheduler to read job configurations and by worker nodes to update job statuses.\n    * Considerations: \n        A relational database like PostgreSQL or MySQL is ideal for structured job data, while NoSQL options like \n        MongoDB can be used for logs or metadata.\n\n    Separate Databases.\n    Different Access Patterns: Job storage requires frequent reads, updates, and transactions, \n         while log storage is write-heavy with occasional reads, often in the form of batch analysis.\n    \n   Optimized for Different Workloads: Using a database like PostgreSQL or Redis for job storage \n         ensures fast job updates and queries, while Elasticsearch or InfluxDB for log storage allows \n         for efficient log indexing, searching, and analysis.\n\n    Scalability Considerations: Using different databases allows each system to scale independently. \n        Log storage systems like Elasticsearch can scale horizontally as the log volume grows, while \n        job storage can focus on maintaining consistency and fast access times.\n\n    \n\n - Monitoring & Alerting\n\n    * Role: Tracks the health of the system and job executions, sending alerts for failures or anomalies.\n    * Interactions: Retrieves data from job storage and job queue to monitor job execution times, failures, and retries.\n    * Considerations: Integration with monitoring tools like Prometheus and Grafana for visual dashboards.\n\n - User/API Clients\n\n    * Role: Interfaces used by users to interact with the scheduler through REST APIs for creating, updating, or querying jobs.\n    * Interactions: Sends requests to the job scheduler and receives updates on job statuses.\n    * Considerations: Ensure authentication and authorization for secure access to job data.\n\n\nThis design provides a scalable, fault-tolerant solution for scheduling and managing distributed tasks \nwhile supporting varied job types, priorities, and dependencies.\n    \n\n - Monitoring & Alerting\n\n    * Role: Tracks the health of the system and job executions, sending alerts for failures or anomalies.\n    * Interactions: Retrieves data from job storage and job queue to monitor job execution times, failures, and retries.\n    * Considerations: Integration with monitoring tools like Prometheus and Grafana for visual dashboards.\n\n - User/API Clients\n\n    * Role: Interfaces used by users to interact with the scheduler through REST APIs for creating, updating, or querying jobs.\n    * Interactions: Sends requests to the job scheduler and receives updates on job statuses.\n    * Considerations: Ensure authentication and authorization for secure access to job data.\n\n\nThis design provides a scalable, fault-tolerant solution for scheduling and managing distributed tasks \nwhile supporting varied job types, priorities, and dependencies.",
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": " Deep Dive into Major Components\n\n - Job Scheduler (Master Node/Leader)\n\n    * Role: \n        The central component that manages job distribution to worker nodes. \n        It maintains a global job queue and assigns jobs to workers. \n    * Interactions: \n        Reads job data from the database and pushes tasks into the job queue. \n        Continuously monitors worker nodes for job completion or failures.\n    * Considerations: \n        Leader election mechanism is needed for high availability, \n        e.g., using Zookeeper or etcd.\n\n - Job Queue (e.g., Redis, RabbitMQ)\n\n    * Role: \n        Stores jobs in a queue for workers to pick up based on their load. Supports \n        prioritized queues to ensure high-priority jobs are executed first.\n    * Interactions: \n        Worker nodes consume jobs from the queue, and the scheduler pushes new jobs or retries into the queue.\n    * Considerations: \n        Choosing a queue with support for priority handling and message acknowledgment is crucial to prevent job loss.\n\n - Worker Nodes\n\n    * Role: \n        Execute jobs by picking them from the job queue. Each worker updates the status of the job \n        in the database upon completion or failure.\n    * Interactions: \n        Interacts with the job queue to pull tasks and with the database to update job statuses.\n    * Considerations: \n        Workers should be stateless to enable horizontal scaling. Use thread pools within workers\n        for parallel job execution.\n\n - Job Storage (SQL/NoSQL Database) : \n    Use different DB for Job storage (Postgres/DynamoDB/MongoDb) and for log storage (TimeSeries InfluxDB/Elasticsearch). \n    Store archived or old logs to S3.\n\n    * Role: Stores job metadata, schedules, execution logs, and history.\n    * Interactions: Used by the scheduler to read job configurations and by worker nodes to update job statuses.\n    * Considerations: \n        A relational database like PostgreSQL or MySQL is ideal for structured job data, while NoSQL options like \n        MongoDB can be used for logs or metadata.\n\n    Separate Databases.\n    Different Access Patterns: Job storage requires frequent reads, updates, and transactions, \n         while log storage is write-heavy with occasional reads, often in the form of batch analysis.\n    \n   Optimized for Different Workloads: Using a database like PostgreSQL or Redis for job storage \n         ensures fast job updates and queries, while Elasticsearch or InfluxDB for log storage allows \n         for efficient log indexing, searching, and analysis.\n\n    Scalability Considerations: Using different databases allows each system to scale independently. \n        Log storage systems like Elasticsearch can scale horizontally as the log volume grows, while \n        job storage can focus on maintaining consistency and fast access times.\n\n    \n\n - Monitoring & Alerting\n\n    * Role: Tracks the health of the system and job executions, sending alerts for failures or anomalies.\n    * Interactions: Retrieves data from job storage and job queue to monitor job execution times, failures, and retries.\n    * Considerations: Integration with monitoring tools like Prometheus and Grafana for visual dashboards.\n\n - User/API Clients\n\n    * Role: Interfaces used by users to interact with the scheduler through REST APIs for creating, updating, or querying jobs.\n    * Interactions: Sends requests to the job scheduler and receives updates on job statuses.\n    * Considerations: Ensure authentication and authorization for secure access to job data.\n\n\nThis design provides a scalable, fault-tolerant solution for scheduling and managing distributed tasks \nwhile supporting varied job types, priorities, and dependencies.\n    \n\n - Monitoring & Alerting\n\n    * Role: Tracks the health of the system and job executions, sending alerts for failures or anomalies.\n    * Interactions: Retrieves data from job storage and job queue to monitor job execution times, failures, and retries.\n    * Considerations: Integration with monitoring tools like Prometheus and Grafana for visual dashboards.\n\n - User/API Clients\n\n    * Role: Interfaces used by users to interact with the scheduler through REST APIs for creating, updating, or querying jobs.\n    * Interactions: Sends requests to the job scheduler and receives updates on job statuses.\n    * Considerations: Ensure authentication and authorization for secure access to job data.\n\n\nThis design provides a scalable, fault-tolerant solution for scheduling and managing distributed tasks \nwhile supporting varied job types, priorities, and dependencies.",
