      "fontFamily": 5,
      "text": "Metrics Monitoring and Aggregation System",
      "textAlign": "center",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Metrics Monitoring and Aggregation System",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "F6pMhP0AHuTJUDKFcUXa5",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -1527.5236983302552,
      "y": 55998.2847360896,
      "width": 1739.9422607421875,
      "height": 5679.4725490113915,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bGG",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 514968408,
      "version": 1548,
      "versionNonce": 168477279,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1772327655383,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Functional\n- Ingestion (push) / Collection\n- Aggregate metrics (min, max, avg, sum, p95, p99) \n  over time windows (1m, 5m, 1h).\n- Storage tiers: hot (recent, high-res), \n   warm (compressed, downsampled), cold (long-term).\n- Should be able Query metrics: time-range queries, \n  label filters, group-by, downsampling hint.\n- Alerts & notifications\n- Cardinality control: guardrails against unbounded \n  label explosion. [Set rules \"\"You can't use high-cardinality \n  labels like user_id directly. You must aggregate them \n  first into something like user_country.\"\"]\n- Multi-Tenancy: The warehouse has separate sections \n  for each team (Tenants). The \"Search Team\" has their \n  own quota and can't use all the space and slow down \n  the \"Notifications Team.\"\n\n\nNon-Functional\n- Scalability: 1M+ metrics/sec ingestion\n- High availability: 99.95% / 99.99% (4 nine) for query & \n  alerting; ingestion should buffer during partial outages.\n- Low Latency: <1s ingestion → queryable, <100ms query (P99)\n  Real-time alerting needs low latency.\n- Durability: No data loss after commit and during node failure.\n  WAL + replication (RF=3), RF=3 stands for Replication \n  Factor 3, means data is stored on three different nodes.\n- Throughput: sustain multi-million samples/sec global ingestion.\n- Cost Efficiency: Old data stored in cheaper archive (S3/AWS glacier)\n- Governance: schema registry + metric linting; deprecation & TTL enforcement.\n\nBack-of-the-Envelope: Let’s estimate scale to size components.\n    Assumptions:\n    - 10,000 servers/microservices\n    - Each emits 100 metrics/sec (e.g., latency, QPS, errors)\n    - Average metric size: 100 bytes (metric name + value + timestamp + 3 tags)\n    \n    Calculations:\n    - Total metrics per second = 10,000 × 100 = 1M/sec\n    - Data rate = 1M × 100 bytes = 100 MB/sec\n    - Daily volume = 100 MB/sec × 86,400 sec ≈ 8.64 TB/day\n    - Yearly volume (raw) ≈ 3.15 PB\n    - With 10:1 compression → ~315 TB/year\n    - Retention: 15 days raw, 1 year downsampled → ~315 TB total\n        - Hot: 15 days with 10secs downsampled\n        - Warm: next 75 days with 1min downsampled\n        - Cold: 365 days with 5min downsampled\n    Interview Script:\n    \"We’re looking at ~100 MB/sec of incoming data — that’s manageable with \n    distributed queues. But yearly storage is ~300+ TB even after compression. \n    So we’ll need tiered storage: hot storage for recent data, cold for historical. \n    Also, 1M metrics/sec means we need parallel ingestion — no single-point bottlenecks. \n    This informs our choice of message queues and storage engines.\"\n\n\nAPI:\nIngest (Push/write): POST /v1/metrics\nQuery: \nGET /v1/metrics/query?metric=cpu.usage&start=ts&end=ts&step=1m\n      → Query aggregated metrics\n\nPOST /v1/query — instant query (expr, ts)\nPOST /v1/query_range — range query (expr, start, end, step, downsample_hint)\n\nGET /v1/labels \nGET /v1/label/<name>/values\n\nAlerting & SLO: \nPOST /v1/alerts — Define alert rules (e.g., CPU > 80% for 5m)\n\nGET /alerts/status\n  → Fetch current triggered alerts\n\nGET /dashboard/:id\n  → Render saved dashboards\n\nMetadata: \nGET /v1/usage — samples/sec, active series, storage by tenant\n\n\n\nDB:\nStorage choices (why)\n*Hot Storage: Hot storage ensures rapid data access when you need it most, \nwhile cold storage offers cost-effective solutions for infrequently accessed data. \n\n- TimeSeries (TSDB) - Hot Storage, e.g., VictoriaMetrics/Cortex/Mimir\n  These are designed for high-write, high-cardinality workloads. \n\n  T_series_index - stores metadata about each unique series\n    Fields/columns: (tenant_id, metric_name, labels, first_ts, last_ts)\n    \n T_samples - stores actual metric data points (timestamp + value)\n   Fields/Columns: (tenant_id, series_id, ts, value)\n\n*Warm Storage (ClickHouse / Bigtable)\n- T_Metrics_1m (tenant_id, metric, labels, ts, avg, min, max, p95)\n(1-minute aggregates for mid-term queries, ~75d retention)\n\nLabelsCatalog (tenant_id, label_name, label_value, last_seen)\n(all label keys/values for filtering and governance)\n\n* Cold Storage (S3/Parquet)\nT_Metrics_5m (partitioned by date)\n(tenant_id, metric, labels, window_start, window_end, sum, count, p99)\n(5-minute rollups for long-term retention, 1y+)\n\n\n\n\n",
      "fontSize": 40.56766106436708,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Functional\n- Ingestion (push) / Collection\n- Aggregate metrics (min, max, avg, sum, p95, p99) \n  over time windows (1m, 5m, 1h).\n- Storage tiers: hot (recent, high-res), \n   warm (compressed, downsampled), cold (long-term).\n- Should be able Query metrics: time-range queries, \n  label filters, group-by, downsampling hint.\n- Alerts & notifications\n- Cardinality control: guardrails against unbounded \n  label explosion. [Set rules \"\"You can't use high-cardinality \n  labels like user_id directly. You must aggregate them \n  first into something like user_country.\"\"]\n- Multi-Tenancy: The warehouse has separate sections \n  for each team (Tenants). The \"Search Team\" has their \n  own quota and can't use all the space and slow down \n  the \"Notifications Team.\"\n\n\nNon-Functional\n- Scalability: 1M+ metrics/sec ingestion\n- High availability: 99.95% / 99.99% (4 nine) for query & \n  alerting; ingestion should buffer during partial outages.\n- Low Latency: <1s ingestion → queryable, <100ms query (P99)\n  Real-time alerting needs low latency.\n- Durability: No data loss after commit and during node failure.\n  WAL + replication (RF=3), RF=3 stands for Replication \n  Factor 3, means data is stored on three different nodes.\n- Throughput: sustain multi-million samples/sec global ingestion.\n- Cost Efficiency: Old data stored in cheaper archive (S3/AWS glacier)\n- Governance: schema registry + metric linting; deprecation & TTL enforcement.\n\nBack-of-the-Envelope: Let’s estimate scale to size components.\n    Assumptions:\n    - 10,000 servers/microservices\n    - Each emits 100 metrics/sec (e.g., latency, QPS, errors)\n    - Average metric size: 100 bytes (metric name + value + timestamp + 3 tags)\n    \n    Calculations:\n    - Total metrics per second = 10,000 × 100 = 1M/sec\n    - Data rate = 1M × 100 bytes = 100 MB/sec\n    - Daily volume = 100 MB/sec × 86,400 sec ≈ 8.64 TB/day\n    - Yearly volume (raw) ≈ 3.15 PB\n    - With 10:1 compression → ~315 TB/year\n    - Retention: 15 days raw, 1 year downsampled → ~315 TB total\n        - Hot: 15 days with 10secs downsampled\n        - Warm: next 75 days with 1min downsampled\n        - Cold: 365 days with 5min downsampled\n    Interview Script:\n    \"We’re looking at ~100 MB/sec of incoming data — that’s manageable with \n    distributed queues. But yearly storage is ~300+ TB even after compression. \n    So we’ll need tiered storage: hot storage for recent data, cold for historical. \n    Also, 1M metrics/sec means we need parallel ingestion — no single-point bottlenecks. \n    This informs our choice of message queues and storage engines.\"\n\n\nAPI:\nIngest (Push/write): POST /v1/metrics\nQuery: \nGET /v1/metrics/query?metric=cpu.usage&start=ts&end=ts&step=1m\n      → Query aggregated metrics\n\nPOST /v1/query — instant query (expr, ts)\nPOST /v1/query_range — range query (expr, start, end, step, downsample_hint)\n\nGET /v1/labels \nGET /v1/label/<name>/values\n\nAlerting & SLO: \nPOST /v1/alerts — Define alert rules (e.g., CPU > 80% for 5m)\n\nGET /alerts/status\n  → Fetch current triggered alerts\n\nGET /dashboard/:id\n  → Render saved dashboards\n\nMetadata: \nGET /v1/usage — samples/sec, active series, storage by tenant\n\n\n\nDB:\nStorage choices (why)\n*Hot Storage: Hot storage ensures rapid data access when you need it most, \nwhile cold storage offers cost-effective solutions for infrequently accessed data. \n\n- TimeSeries (TSDB) - Hot Storage, e.g., VictoriaMetrics/Cortex/Mimir\n  These are designed for high-write, high-cardinality workloads. \n\n  T_series_index - stores metadata about each unique series\n    Fields/columns: (tenant_id, metric_name, labels, first_ts, last_ts)\n    \n T_samples - stores actual metric data points (timestamp + value)\n   Fields/Columns: (tenant_id, series_id, ts, value)\n\n*Warm Storage (ClickHouse / Bigtable)\n- T_Metrics_1m (tenant_id, metric, labels, ts, avg, min, max, p95)\n(1-minute aggregates for mid-term queries, ~75d retention)\n\nLabelsCatalog (tenant_id, label_name, label_value, last_seen)\n(all label keys/values for filtering and governance)\n\n* Cold Storage (S3/Parquet)\nT_Metrics_5m (partitioned by date)\n(tenant_id, metric, labels, window_start, window_end, sum, count, p99)\n(5-minute rollups for long-term retention, 1y+)\n\n\n\n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
