      "fontSize": 68.06171603180479,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "text": "Inverted Index od LinkedIn Posts",
      "textAlign": "center",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Inverted Index od LinkedIn Posts",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "a5lQWPSPXk8D9ayyZBbrl",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -1961.4722074363126,
      "y": 62026.777488381456,
      "width": 1346.5435791015625,
      "height": 135,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#a5d8ff",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bJD",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 450461992,
      "version": 120,
      "versionNonce": 243204392,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1756083378590,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Q. Design a system which takes stream of linkedin posts and form a inverted index \nof all the words in the post. The user will query a list of words, you have to return \nall the post ids which has all the given list of words.",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Q. Design a system which takes stream of linkedin posts and form a inverted index \nof all the words in the post. The user will query a list of words, you have to return \nall the post ids which has all the given list of words.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "2vZ3rBynR1U9NAvhTZTnS",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -791.4829885236713,
      "y": 62211.37860101271,
      "width": 1949.8675537109375,
      "height": 4500,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#a5d8ff",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bJF",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1314386984,
      "version": 645,
      "versionNonce": 1713123348,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1756159320697,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Functional: \n- Consumes a stream of LinkedIn posts.\n- Extracts words from post and Tokenize (remove punctuation, lowercase, etc.).\n- Builds and maintains inverted index, e.g. word → [post_id1, post_id2, ...]\n- Update inverted index as new posts arrive.\n- Supports conjunctive queries: given a list of words, return all post IDs that contain all of them.\n\nNon-Functional: \n- Latency Query: <100ms, Ingestion: <1s, so new posts appear in search quickly.\n- Throughput: 10K posts/sec, 5K queries/sec — LinkedIn has massive engagement.\n- High availability (>99.9%) and fault tolerance, using replication and redundancy.\n- Durability: Replication factor ≥ 3; WAL/commit log; S3 snapshots.\n- Consistency: Eventually consistent index. Trade-off for availability and speed.\n- Fault Tolerance: Survive node failures\n- Observability via metrics, logging, and tracing — because if it breaks, we need to know why fast.\"\n- Cost Efficiency: Old data stored in cheaper archive (S3/AWS glacier)\n\nBack-of-the-envelop: \n* Assumptions:\n- 10K posts per sec (peak) with AVG size: ~50 words\n- Avg word length: 6 characters → ~300 bytes per post\n- Total words/sec: 10K × 50 = 500K words/sec\n\n- Unique words: Assume 1M distinct words (English + jargon)\n- Post lifetime: 1 year → ~315M posts/year\n- Query rate: 5K QPS (complex queries)\n\n* Storage Estimation:\n- Each word maps to a list of post IDs.\n- Assume average 10K posts per word (for popular words it will be higher).\n- Each post ID: 8 bytes (long)\n- Total storage: 1M words × 10K post IDs × 8 bytes = 80 GB\n  But skewed: \"hiring\" may have 10M entries → hot keys.\n    → Estimate: 100–200 GB of index data.\n\n* Throughput:\nNeed to process 500K word updates/sec.\nQuery: 5K QPS, each query intersects 2–5 word lists.\n\n\n\nAPI:\n- GET /search?q=word1+word2\n    Response: { \"post_ids\": [123, 456, 789], \"took_ms\": 45 }\n\n*Internal (Admin)\n  - POST /posts (internal, for ingestion) - ingestion done via stream\n    but keep it for testing. Not public.\n    Payload: { \"post_id\": 123, \"text\": \"I am a machine learning engineer...\" }\n\n - POST /v1/reindex?from=timestamp — The definition of a \"word\" might change, \n  or they might want to improve how they're stored. This tells the system, \"Go back \n  and rebuild the entire index for all posts from a certain time.\" (This is a \"rolling reindex\").\n\n - POST /v1/refresh_visibility — A user might change a post from \"Public\" to \n\"Connections Only,\" or delete their account. This forces the search index to \nimmediately double-check with the \"visibility service\" to ensure hidden posts \ndon't appear in search results..\n\n \n\nDB: \n* Choice\n- Primary (Option A): OpenSearch/Elasticsearch for inverted index. -- we'll choose OpenSearch\n  Why: battle-tested full-text engine, shard routing, compression, skip data structures, query DSL, ops tooling.\n\n- Metadata/controls: PostgreSQL (or Aurora) for job state, schema versions.\n- Cache: Redis for term DF & small postings caches.\n- Streaming: Kafka (ingestion buffer, replay, backfill).\n- Object store: S3 for snapshots, cold tiers.\n\n* Logical Tables (field names only)\n- Post stream (Kafka value schema)\n    post_id, text, lang, author_id, visibility, created_at, updated_at, op (upsert/delete)\n\n- OpenSearch index mapping (document = post)\n\n_id = post_id\ntext: analyzed (custom analyzer per language)\nlang: keyword\nvisibility: keyword\ncreated_at: date\n\n- PostgreSQL (operational metadata)\n  reindex_jobs(job_id, status, start_ts, end_ts, from_ts, shard_plan_json)\n    -- log of every time an admin triggers a \"reindex.\" \n\nterm_hotset(term, df, updated_at)\n    -- A small table of the most popular search terms (term) and how many \n        posts contain them (df - Document Frequency). This is for monitoring.\n\ndelete_tombstones(post_id, ts) (mirror to ensure SLA)\nvisibility_overrides(post_id, visibility, ts)\n -- A guaranteed list of every post that was deleted or had its visibility changed. \n   Ensures the system never forgets to process a delete, even if something goes wrong temporarily.\n\nWhy these choices?\n- Search engine handles postings, compression, skip lists, intersection efficiently.\n - SQL keeps operator state reliable; Kafka is the durable bus; Redis cuts tail on hot metadata.\n",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Functional: \n- Consumes a stream of LinkedIn posts.\n- Extracts words from post and Tokenize (remove punctuation, lowercase, etc.).\n- Builds and maintains inverted index, e.g. word → [post_id1, post_id2, ...]\n- Update inverted index as new posts arrive.\n- Supports conjunctive queries: given a list of words, return all post IDs that contain all of them.\n\nNon-Functional: \n- Latency Query: <100ms, Ingestion: <1s, so new posts appear in search quickly.\n- Throughput: 10K posts/sec, 5K queries/sec — LinkedIn has massive engagement.\n- High availability (>99.9%) and fault tolerance, using replication and redundancy.\n- Durability: Replication factor ≥ 3; WAL/commit log; S3 snapshots.\n- Consistency: Eventually consistent index. Trade-off for availability and speed.\n- Fault Tolerance: Survive node failures\n- Observability via metrics, logging, and tracing — because if it breaks, we need to know why fast.\"\n- Cost Efficiency: Old data stored in cheaper archive (S3/AWS glacier)\n\nBack-of-the-envelop: \n* Assumptions:\n- 10K posts per sec (peak) with AVG size: ~50 words\n- Avg word length: 6 characters → ~300 bytes per post\n- Total words/sec: 10K × 50 = 500K words/sec\n\n- Unique words: Assume 1M distinct words (English + jargon)\n- Post lifetime: 1 year → ~315M posts/year\n- Query rate: 5K QPS (complex queries)\n\n* Storage Estimation:\n- Each word maps to a list of post IDs.\n- Assume average 10K posts per word (for popular words it will be higher).\n- Each post ID: 8 bytes (long)\n- Total storage: 1M words × 10K post IDs × 8 bytes = 80 GB\n  But skewed: \"hiring\" may have 10M entries → hot keys.\n    → Estimate: 100–200 GB of index data.\n\n* Throughput:\nNeed to process 500K word updates/sec.\nQuery: 5K QPS, each query intersects 2–5 word lists.\n\n\n\nAPI:\n- GET /search?q=word1+word2\n    Response: { \"post_ids\": [123, 456, 789], \"took_ms\": 45 }\n\n*Internal (Admin)\n  - POST /posts (internal, for ingestion) - ingestion done via stream\n    but keep it for testing. Not public.\n    Payload: { \"post_id\": 123, \"text\": \"I am a machine learning engineer...\" }\n\n - POST /v1/reindex?from=timestamp — The definition of a \"word\" might change, \n  or they might want to improve how they're stored. This tells the system, \"Go back \n  and rebuild the entire index for all posts from a certain time.\" (This is a \"rolling reindex\").\n\n - POST /v1/refresh_visibility — A user might change a post from \"Public\" to \n\"Connections Only,\" or delete their account. This forces the search index to \nimmediately double-check with the \"visibility service\" to ensure hidden posts \ndon't appear in search results..\n\n \n\nDB: \n* Choice\n- Primary (Option A): OpenSearch/Elasticsearch for inverted index. -- we'll choose OpenSearch\n  Why: battle-tested full-text engine, shard routing, compression, skip data structures, query DSL, ops tooling.\n\n- Metadata/controls: PostgreSQL (or Aurora) for job state, schema versions.\n- Cache: Redis for term DF & small postings caches.\n- Streaming: Kafka (ingestion buffer, replay, backfill).\n- Object store: S3 for snapshots, cold tiers.\n\n* Logical Tables (field names only)\n- Post stream (Kafka value schema)\n    post_id, text, lang, author_id, visibility, created_at, updated_at, op (upsert/delete)\n\n- OpenSearch index mapping (document = post)\n\n_id = post_id\ntext: analyzed (custom analyzer per language)\nlang: keyword\nvisibility: keyword\ncreated_at: date\n\n- PostgreSQL (operational metadata)\n  reindex_jobs(job_id, status, start_ts, end_ts, from_ts, shard_plan_json)\n    -- log of every time an admin triggers a \"reindex.\" \n\nterm_hotset(term, df, updated_at)\n    -- A small table of the most popular search terms (term) and how many \n        posts contain them (df - Document Frequency). This is for monitoring.\n\ndelete_tombstones(post_id, ts) (mirror to ensure SLA)\nvisibility_overrides(post_id, visibility, ts)\n -- A guaranteed list of every post that was deleted or had its visibility changed. \n   Ensures the system never forgets to process a delete, even if something goes wrong temporarily.\n\nWhy these choices?\n- Search engine handles postings, compression, skip lists, intersection efficiently.\n - SQL keeps operator state reliable; Kafka is the durable bus; Redis cuts tail on hot metadata.\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "sVeOAvNcnuoV8ryb6CkGY",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -1989.1939867216797,
      "y": 62817.98783052667,
      "width": 1092.70751953125,
      "height": 225,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#f08c00",
      "backgroundColor": "#a5d8ff",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bJG",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 402266664,
      "version": 149,
      "versionNonce": 730418264,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1756136116183,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Interview script: \n“I’ll trade strict read-your-writes for high availability. \nDeletes/visibility changes propagate synchronously to \na ‘visibility filter’ so they take effect on queries \nimmediately, while index updates can be eventually consistent.”",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Interview script: \n“I’ll trade strict read-your-writes for high availability. \nDeletes/visibility changes propagate synchronously to \na ‘visibility filter’ so they take effect on queries \nimmediately, while index updates can be eventually consistent.”",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "47_xhs4IXWMF-b2z2oKpx",
